basicQuestions.answerText:
Symptoms of Horner's syndrome typically&nbsp;include drooping of the upper eyelid (ptosis), constriction of the pupil (miosis), sinking of the eyeball into the face, and decreased sweating on the affected side of the face (<a href="https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/003219.htm" target="_blank">anhidrosis</a>). These symptoms may vary and other symptoms may occur depending on the underlying cause of the condition.[334][335] Other symptoms which may be seen include the inability to completely close or open the eyelid, facial flushing, headaches, and pain.[335][337]&nbsp;<br />
<br />
Heterochromia iridium (i.e., a relative deficiency of pigment in the iris  of affected side of the face) is usually present when the syndrome is congenital or caused by a lesion that has occurred before the age of 1-2 years of age.[337]&nbsp;
